---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Med-Surgical 26 — Lucia Hoyos"
  description="Unfolding case study: Postoperative Colostomy Care and Hyperkalemia Secondary to Medication Error (MED-26)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/med-surgical/`}>Med-Surgical</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Med-Surgical 26 — Lucia Hoyos</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">GI / Medication Safety</span>
    <h1>Med-Surgical 26 — Lucia Hoyos</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Postoperative Colostomy Care and Hyperkalemia Secondary to Medication Error</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Lucia Hoyos, 65 years, Hispanic Female</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20–25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20–25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- PHASE 1 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You are the nurse on the postoperative med-surgical unit. You are receiving Lucia Hoyos from the PACU following transverse colostomy creation. You enter the room and immediately notice Lucia is confused and disoriented.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Lucia Hoyos</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / Gender</th><td>65 years · Female · Hispanic</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Post transverse colostomy (abdominal surgery)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Mental Status</th><td><strong>CONFUSED</strong> — disoriented on arrival</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Colostomy</th><td>Colostomy pouch in place; stoma visible</td></tr>
            <tr><th>IV Fluids</th><td>D5½NS running</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergies</th><td>Review MAR</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🚨 First Action — Fall Safety</h3>
        <div class="callout callout-danger" style="margin-bottom: 0;">
          <strong>FIRST: Place bed in LOWEST position immediately.</strong>
          <p>Lucia is confused and disoriented. She is reaching toward her colostomy pouch. A confused patient on a high bed is at immediate fall risk. Lowering the bed is the priority safety action before any assessment or intervention.</p>
          <ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 1.25rem;">
            <li>Lower bed to lowest position</li>
            <li>Ensure both siderails up (leave one down only during active care)</li>
            <li>Call light within reach</li>
            <li>Apply fall precaution signage</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>Lucia is in bed, attempting to pull at her colostomy pouch. She does not know where she is. She asks, "¿Dónde estoy?" (Where am I?). The colostomy pouch is intact with stoma visible through the clear window. D5½NS is infusing through a peripheral IV in her left arm.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What causes postoperative confusion?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Common causes of postoperative confusion (AEIOU-TIPS mnemonic):</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Hypoxia</strong> — most dangerous and most common; SpO₂ &lt; 90% impairs cerebral oxygenation immediately</li>
          <li><strong>Electrolyte imbalance</strong> — hyperkalemia (as in Lucia's case) affects cardiac output → reduced cerebral perfusion → confusion</li>
          <li><strong>Pain medications / anesthesia</strong> — opioids and general anesthesia agents cause residual cognitive effects, especially in older adults</li>
          <li><strong>Age</strong> — patients over 65 are at significantly higher risk for postoperative delirium (POD)</li>
          <li><strong>Unfamiliar environment</strong> — ICU psychosis / hospital disorientation</li>
          <li><strong>Urinary retention</strong> — a distended bladder can cause acute agitation in older adults</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Priority assessment:</strong> Check SpO₂ first — hypoxia is the most immediately reversible cause and the most dangerous.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Bed is lowered. You secure Lucia's safety and proceed with stoma assessment…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 2 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Colostomy Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Lucia is now calmer. You perform your colostomy assessment. The pouch is approximately 1/3 full with liquid stool. You inspect the stoma and peristomal skin carefully.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>👁️ Stoma Assessment — Normal vs. Abnormal</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Normal</th><th>Abnormal — Notify Provider</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Color</td><td>Pink to red (like oral mucosa)</td><td>Purple, dark red, or black — necrosis</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Moisture</td><td>Moist, shiny</td><td>Dry, dull</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Position</td><td>Slightly protruding (0.5–1.5 cm)</td><td>Sunken (retracted) or prolapsed</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Edges</td><td>Intact, adhered to skin</td><td>Separation (mucocutaneous separation)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Bleeding</td><td>Minor oozing from edges (normal post-op)</td><td>Active bleeding or frank hemorrhage</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🛍️ Colostomy Pouch Management</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li>Empty pouch when <strong>1/3 to 1/2 full</strong> — excess weight breaks the seal</li>
          <li>Change pouching system every <strong>3–7 days</strong> or when leaking</li>
          <li><strong>Measure stoma at each change</strong> — stoma shrinks as postoperative swelling resolves</li>
          <li>Cut wafer opening to fit stoma (1/8 inch border around stoma)</li>
          <li>Clean with warm water only — no soap on stoma itself</li>
          <li>Dry peristomal skin <strong>completely</strong> before applying new wafer</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🩺 Peristomal Skin Assessment</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Normal Finding</th><th>Concerning Finding</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Peristomal skin</td><td>Intact, same color as surrounding skin</td><td>Redness, weeping, denudation from effluent contact</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Wafer seal</td><td>Adherent, no leakage around edges</td><td>Lifting, tunneling, or leakage — change system now</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Stoma-skin junction</td><td>Clean, adherent, no separation</td><td>Mucocutaneous separation — wound care consult</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How do you recognize stoma necrosis, and why is it an emergency?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Recognizing stoma necrosis:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Color change from normal pink/red → <strong>dark purple, maroon, or black</strong></li>
          <li>Stoma becomes dry, dull, or non-moist</li>
          <li>May be odorous</li>
          <li>Usually occurs within 24–72 hours postoperatively</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Why it is an emergency:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Necrosis indicates compromised blood supply to the stoma — the bowel segment is dying</li>
          <li>Without intervention, the stoma will slough off, leading to bowel contents leaking into the abdomen (peritonitis)</li>
          <li>Surgical revision is required immediately</li>
          <li><strong>Action:</strong> Do NOT attempt to push or manipulate a dark stoma. Cover with moist gauze and call provider STAT.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Stoma is pink and moist — healthy. You review the EHR and discover an alarming lab value…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 3 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Recognizing Hyperkalemia</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You review Lucia's most recent labs. Her serum potassium is 6.2 mEq/L. You immediately review the MAR and identify that she received excessive potassium in her IV fluids — a medication error.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🧪 Potassium Lab Values</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Value</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Normal</td><td>3.5–5.0 mEq/L</td><td>Continue monitoring</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Mild hyperkalemia</td><td>5.1–6.0 mEq/L</td><td>Notify provider; cardiac monitor</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Moderate hyperkalemia</td><td>6.1–7.0 mEq/L</td><td><strong>Lucia: 6.2</strong> — STOP K⁺ sources; urgent treatment</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Severe hyperkalemia</td><td>&gt; 7.0 mEq/L</td><td>Life-threatening — STAT interventions</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💓 ECG Changes in Hyperkalemia</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>ECG Finding</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Early (K⁺ 5.5–6.5)</td><td><strong>Peaked T waves</strong> — earliest warning sign</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Moderate (K⁺ 6.5–7.5)</td><td>Prolonged PR interval · Widened QRS complex</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Severe (K⁺ &gt; 7.5)</td><td>Sine wave pattern (P waves merge with QRS)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Critical</td><td>Ventricular fibrillation → cardiac arrest</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-danger">
      <strong>🚨 Stop All Potassium-Containing IV Fluids — Immediately</strong>
      <p>Lucia's D5½NS may have had additional potassium added. <strong>Stop the current infusion now.</strong> Switch to a potassium-free IV solution per provider order. Place Lucia on continuous cardiac monitoring. Obtain a 12-lead ECG. Notify the provider of elevated K⁺ and suspected medication error.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why are peaked T waves the early warning sign of hyperkalemia?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Pathophysiology of peaked T waves:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Potassium is the primary intracellular cation — its concentration gradient across cardiac cell membranes determines the resting membrane potential</li>
          <li>When extracellular K⁺ rises, the resting membrane potential shifts closer to the threshold potential → cells become hyperexcitable</li>
          <li>This manifests on ECG as <strong>tall, narrow, symmetric peaked T waves</strong> — representing abnormally rapid repolarization</li>
          <li>As K⁺ continues to rise, the resting membrane potential eventually exceeds threshold → cells cannot depolarize properly → conduction slows → QRS widens → ventricular fibrillation risk escalates</li>
          <li><strong>Clinical significance:</strong> Peaked T waves are the window of opportunity — treat before QRS widening begins</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Potassium sources stopped. Provider notified. You implement treatment orders…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 4 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Managing Hyperkalemia</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">The provider has ordered a treatment sequence for Lucia's hyperkalemia. You prepare to implement the orders in priority order, understanding the mechanism of each intervention.</p>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>💊 Hyperkalemia Treatment Sequence</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Treatment</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Onset</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>1</strong></td>
            <td><strong>IV Calcium Gluconate</strong></td>
            <td>Stabilizes cardiac cell membrane — does NOT lower K⁺</td>
            <td>Immediate (1–3 min)</td>
            <td>Given FIRST in cardiac emergency; temporary protection only</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>2</strong></td>
            <td><strong>Regular Insulin + Dextrose IV</strong></td>
            <td>Insulin drives K⁺ into cells (redistributes); dextrose prevents hypoglycemia</td>
            <td>15–30 min</td>
            <td>Always give dextrose simultaneously; monitor BG q30–60 min</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>3</strong></td>
            <td><strong>Kayexalate (Sodium Polystyrene Sulfonate)</strong></td>
            <td>Cation exchange resin — removes K⁺ via GI tract in stool</td>
            <td>Hours</td>
            <td>Actual K⁺ removal; use with caution post-bowel surgery</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>4</strong></td>
            <td><strong>Furosemide IV</strong></td>
            <td>Loop diuretic — promotes renal K⁺ excretion</td>
            <td>Hours</td>
            <td>Actual K⁺ removal; requires functioning kidneys</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <strong>⚠️ Medication Error — Report and Document</strong>
      <p>A medication error caused Lucia's hyperkalemia. You must complete an <strong>incident report</strong> promptly, separate from the medical record. Document: what happened, when it was discovered, what potassium was administered, the patient's current clinical status, and interventions taken. The incident report is for quality improvement — it is not an admission of fault. Do NOT document "incident report filed" in the medical record.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Which treatments temporarily redistribute K⁺ vs. permanently remove it?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Temporary redistribution (does not remove K⁺ from body):</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>IV Calcium gluconate</strong> — only cardiac membrane protection; K⁺ level unchanged</li>
          <li><strong>Insulin + Dextrose</strong> — shifts K⁺ into cells temporarily; K⁺ returns to extracellular space as insulin effect wanes (usually 4–6 hours)</li>
          <li><strong>Sodium bicarbonate</strong> — alkalinizes serum; K⁺ shifts into cells to exchange for H⁺; temporary</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Permanent removal (eliminates K⁺ from body):</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Kayexalate</strong> — GI tract eliminates K⁺ in stool; takes hours; may cause constipation or bowel obstruction</li>
          <li><strong>Furosemide</strong> — renal excretion; effective only with intact kidney function</li>
          <li><strong>Hemodialysis</strong> — most effective and fastest for severe/refractory hyperkalemia</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Clinical principle:</strong> Redistributive treatments buy time to protect the heart while the permanent removal methods begin working. Both types are needed together.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Lucia's K⁺ is trending down. You shift focus to colostomy self-care education…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 5 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Colostomy Patient Education</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Lucia is more alert after treatment. Her family has arrived. You begin colostomy discharge education, keeping in mind Lucia's cultural background and the importance of family-centered care for many Hispanic patients.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🛍️ Self-Care Skills — Return Demonstration</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Skill</th><th>Key Teaching Points</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Empty the pouch</td><td>Lift toilet seat; unroll end of pouch; drain; wipe; re-roll and secure</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Change the pouch</td><td>Warm water to loosen wafer; clean stoma gently; dry completely; measure stoma; cut wafer; apply and press 30 seconds</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Assess the stoma</td><td>Pink and moist = healthy; dark/dry = call provider</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🥦 Dietary Guidance</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li>Avoid gas-producing foods initially (beans, cabbage, broccoli, carbonated drinks)</li>
          <li>Chew food thoroughly — prevents food blockage at stoma</li>
          <li>Stay well hydrated — liquid stool from transverse colostomy increases dehydration risk</li>
          <li>Introduce new foods one at a time to identify what increases output</li>
          <li>No specific permanent dietary restrictions — individualize over time</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>📞 When to Call the Provider</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>No stoma output for 4–6 hours</td><td>Possible blockage — do not self-treat</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Stoma dark, purple, or black</td><td>Necrosis — emergency; call immediately</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Abdominal cramping with no output</td><td>Obstruction or ileus</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Excessive bleeding from stoma</td><td>Not normal; requires evaluation</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Skin breakdown around stoma</td><td>Effluent contact — needs pouching system adjustment</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Fever &gt; 38°C (100.4°F)</td><td>Possible infection; call provider</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How do you provide culturally sensitive care for Lucia, a Hispanic patient with a new colostomy?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Cultural sensitivity considerations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Language:</strong> Assess Lucia's preferred language for teaching. Provide written materials in Spanish if needed. Use a professional interpreter — not family members — for medical discussions to ensure accuracy and privacy</li>
          <li><strong>Family involvement:</strong> Many Hispanic patients prefer family-centered decision making (<em>familismo</em>). Include family in education sessions with Lucia's permission. Teach family members colostomy care as well</li>
          <li><strong>Body image and dignity:</strong> A colostomy can be especially distressing if it conflicts with cultural norms around bodily cleanliness or femininity. Validate Lucia's feelings without minimizing them</li>
          <li><strong>Referral to WOCN (Wound, Ostomy, Continence Nurse):</strong> Ostomy nurses provide expert individualized education and emotional support — request a consult for all new ostomy patients</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid assumptions:</strong> Not all Hispanic patients share the same values or preferences — assess Lucia's individual needs rather than applying generalizations</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Education complete. You document the medication error and formulate nursing diagnoses…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 6 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase6">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 6</span>
      <h2>Medication Error Reporting + Nursing Diagnoses</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>📝 Incident Report — Required Elements</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Element</th><th>Content for Lucia's Case</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>What happened</td><td>Excess potassium administered via IV fluids; resulting in hyperkalemia (K⁺ 6.2 mEq/L)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>When discovered</td><td>Date and time nurse identified error on MAR review</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Who was involved</td><td>Patient (Lucia Hoyos), nurse discovering error, nurse/provider who administered or ordered</td></tr>
          <tr><td>How discovered</td><td>Lab review of serum potassium combined with MAR audit</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Patient outcome</td><td>Confusion, ECG changes; treated with calcium gluconate, insulin/dextrose, Kayexalate, furosemide; K⁺ trending to normal</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Corrective action</td><td>Potassium-containing fluids stopped; provider notified; treatment initiated; incident report filed</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <h3>📋 Priority Nursing Diagnoses</h3>
    <div class="dx-rank-list">
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">1</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Decreased Cardiac Output</strong><div class="dx-aeb">r/t hyperkalemia secondary to medication error AEB: K⁺ 6.2 mEq/L; potential ECG changes; continuous cardiac monitoring in place</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">2</span>
        <div><strong>Acute Confusion</strong><div class="dx-aeb">r/t hypoxia and electrolyte imbalance secondary to cardiac effects of hyperkalemia AEB: disorientation, reaching toward colostomy pouch, not knowing location</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">3</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Falls</strong><div class="dx-aeb">r/t acute confusion and postoperative weakness AEB: confused patient in postoperative bed; bed placed in lowest position as first nursing action</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">4</span>
        <div><strong>Impaired Skin Integrity</strong><div class="dx-aeb">r/t colostomy effluent contact with peristomal skin AEB: new colostomy with liquid output; skin integrity dependent on proper pouching technique</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">5</span>
        <div><strong>Deficient Knowledge</strong><div class="dx-aeb">r/t colostomy care, dietary modifications, and self-management AEB: new ostomy; first postoperative day; family present and engaged in education</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Calling the Provider About Lucia Hoyos</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>Calling about Lucia Hoyos, a 65-year-old Hispanic female who is postoperative from transverse colostomy. I have identified that she received an incorrect amount of potassium in her IV fluids — I believe there has been a medication error. She is now confused, and her most recent potassium is 6.2 mEq/L.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>She is receiving D5½NS post-surgery. The potassium error was identified when I reviewed her medication administration record. She has no prior renal disease on record. She is on the cardiac monitor. She was oriented and alert in the PACU per handoff.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>K⁺ is 6.2 mEq/L — moderate hyperkalemia. ECG shows peaked T waves. She is confused and at fall risk — bed is in lowest position. SpO₂ is 92% on room air. I have stopped the current IV fluids. Vitals: [insert current values].</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting STAT orders for: IV calcium gluconate, regular insulin with dextrose IV, Kayexalate, and furosemide IV for hyperkalemia management. Also requesting a repeat BMP in 2 hours and supplemental oxygen order. A medication incident report will be completed. Shall I proceed with anything immediately?</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX A: Medications -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-a">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Class</th><th>Key Nursing Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>D5½NS (Dextrose 5% in ½ Normal Saline)</strong></td>
          <td>IV fluid — hypertonic</td>
          <td>Slightly hypertonic (tonicity ≈ 406 mOsm/L); provides approximately 170 kcal/L from dextrose. Used for postoperative hydration. Can carry added electrolytes — verify additives against order. If K⁺ was incorrectly added, can cause hyperkalemia.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Potassium Chloride (KCl) IV</strong> <span class="badge-danger">HIGH ALERT</span></td>
          <td>Electrolyte supplement</td>
          <td>Must NEVER be given undiluted IV push — concentrated KCl causes fatal cardiac arrest. Must be diluted and infused slowly per protocol. Two-nurse verification required. Maximum peripheral infusion rate: 10 mEq/hr. Medication error with excess KCl caused Lucia's hyperkalemia.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Regular Insulin IV</strong> <span class="badge-danger">HIGH ALERT</span></td>
          <td>Antidiabetic — rapid-acting</td>
          <td>For hyperkalemia: stimulates Na-K-ATPase → drives K⁺ from extracellular fluid into cells (temporary redistribution only — does not remove K⁺). Always give with dextrose to prevent hypoglycemia. Monitor blood glucose every 30–60 min. Different mechanism than insulin used for diabetes — applies to all patients, not just diabetics.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Kayexalate (Sodium Polystyrene Sulfonate)</strong></td>
          <td>Cation exchange resin</td>
          <td>Sodium ions exchange for potassium ions in GI tract → K⁺ excreted in stool. PO or rectal enema. Takes hours to work. Use with caution post-bowel surgery (risk of bowel obstruction). Monitor stool output and K⁺ levels. Can cause hypokalemia if excessive.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Furosemide (Lasix) IV</strong></td>
          <td>Loop diuretic</td>
          <td>Inhibits K⁺ reabsorption in loop of Henle → promotes renal K⁺ excretion. Requires functioning kidneys. Monitor urine output, blood pressure, and electrolytes. Also causes Na⁺, Mg²⁺, Ca²⁺ loss — monitor BMP.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: Which statement about potential causes of hypokalemia is correct?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Illnesses resulting in diarrhea and vomiting may cause hypokalemia.</strong> GI losses are a major cause of low potassium — both diarrhea and vomiting result in significant potassium loss. Note: Renal disease, ACE inhibitors, and tissue breakdown are associated with <em>hyper</em>kalemia (elevated potassium), not hypokalemia. This scenario involves hyperkalemia from a medication error — understanding the opposite condition (hypokalemia from GI losses) reinforces knowledge of potassium regulation.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: Which statement about Lucia's D5½NS infusion is correct?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>This solution is hypertonic and provides approximately 170 calories per liter.</strong> D5½NS contains dextrose 5% plus 0.45% sodium chloride. The dextrose provides approximately 170 kcal/L. The total tonicity is approximately 406 mOsm/L, making it a slightly hypertonic solution relative to plasma (normal plasma ≈ 280–295 mOsm/L). The solution is not isotonic, it does not act primarily to expand intravascular volume (like 0.9% NS does), and it is not hypotonic.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: Lucia is postoperative and confused. Which nursing intervention is indicated first?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Placing the bed in a low position.</strong> Postoperative confusion creates an immediate fall risk. The first nursing action is always to ensure physical safety — lowering the bed minimizes injury if a confused patient attempts to get out of bed. Assessment of confusion causes, contacting the physician, and modifying medications are all important but secondary to immediate safety. Restraints should be avoided as a first intervention — they cause injury, increase agitation, and have limited evidence of preventing falls.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: When assessing areas of ecchymosis, is palpation alone sufficient?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>False — assessment requires both visualization AND palpation.</strong> Visual inspection identifies color changes (bruising, pallor, erythema) and surface irregularities. Palpation detects changes in temperature (warmth may indicate infection or pressure injury stage 1), texture changes, and tenderness. Neither modality alone provides a complete assessment. This is particularly important when assessing bony prominences and pressure injury risk areas where deep tissue damage may not yet be visible on the surface.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What is the correct blood product administration consideration for a postoperative patient?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Only normal saline (0.9% NaCl) may be administered with blood products.</strong> Lactated Ringer's (LR) contains calcium, which can cause clotting in the blood product tubing. Dextrose-containing solutions (D5W, D5½NS) cause hemolysis (red blood cell destruction) when mixed with blood. No other IV fluid or medication should be co-administered with blood through the same line without first flushing with normal saline and verifying compatibility.</p></div>
    </details>
  </div>

